Hi Max,

Thanks.
I do have a camper-it is an ez-camper. Mine has always been pretty loud, but
there were many many reasons for that. Including-the window seals on the
crank out windows, were practically not there-so the glass rattled. I dont
know if any of the doors really sealed well. They still dont seal great,
but they are new, and seal much better.

Ez-camper actually did a decent job shoving foam behind all the panels of
the bus. There wasnt any rust under the foam either, which was good. I
really want a quiet bus, I like to either listen to the radio, or talk to my
passengers, and this was always difficult before. Also I noticed I always
got tired pretty quickly driving my bus on longer trips. I then read a post
on the list-linking road noise to fatigue, and it made sense. I want to be
able to take long road trips, without worrying about the road noise tiring
me out. I figure a quieter bus, means more road trips! Although I think if
it is too quiet inside, I will miss the noise of rain on the roof, which I
always loved ;)

I like the two tone on the seats, did you make the seat covers yourself? How
hard was it? I noticed you put a wood or faux wood floor in. I might suggest
putting a carpet in on the floors, I had that in my bus before and noticed a
difference. This helps absorb the sound pretty good. I used some carpet
samples from my office-they were an industrial carpet that had a heavy vinyl
or rubber type backing, it came in squares, and was easy to put in and take
out. I think I may use something from Flor, there product looks similar.

-Kevin
Jamaica Plain, MA
'69 single cab
'65 Kombi

